Mutex (short for "mutual exclusion") is a synchronization primitive in C++ used to protect shared resources or critical sections of code in a multithreaded program. A mutex ensures that only one thread can access the protected resource at a time, preventing data races and maintaining data consistency.

Here's an overview of how to use mutexes in C++:

1. **Include the `` header:**
   ```cpp
   #include 
